The [[discography]] of Finnish [[symphonic metal]] band [[Nightwish]] consists of seven [[studio album]]s, one [[extended play]], four [[live albums]], seven [[compilation albums|compilations]], thirteen [[music video]]s and nineteen [[Single (music)|singles]]. The band was formed in 1996 by songwriter and keyboardist [[Tuomas Holopainen]], guitarist [[Emppu Vuorinen]], and former vocalist [[Tarja Turunen]]; Nightwish's current line-up has five members although Turunen has been replaced by [[Anette Olzon]] and the original bassist, [[Sami Vänskä]], has been replaced by [[Marco Hietala]], who also took over the male vocalist part.<ref name="nw bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.nightwish.com/en/band/biography|title=The band- Biography: The history of Nightwish|accessdate=2010-06-05|work=Nightwish.com}}</ref>

Although Nightwish has been popular in Finland since 1997 when they released their debut album, ''[[Angels Fall First]]'',<ref name="aff">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/angels-fall-first-r502851|title=Angels Fall First – Nightwish|accessdate=2010-06-05|publisher=Rovi Corporation|work=Allmusic}}</ref> they did not achieve worldwide fame until the release of the albums ''[[Oceanborn]]'', ''[[Wishmaster (album)|Wishmaster]]'' and ''[[Century Child]]'', which were released in 1998, 2000 and 2002, respectively.<ref name="oc">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/oceanborn-r429983|title=Oceanborn – Nightwish|accessdate=2010-06-05|publisher=Rovi Corporation|work=Allmusic}}</ref><ref name="wm">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wishmaster-r491543|title=Wishmaster – Nightwish|accessdate=2010-06-05|publisher=Rovi Corporation|work=Allmusic}}</ref><ref name="cc">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/century-child-r641059|title=Century Child – Nightwish|accessdate=2010-06-05|publisher=Rovi Corporation|work=Allmusic}}</ref> The 2004 album, ''[[Once (Nightwish album)|Once]]'', had sold more than one million copies by the end of 2005 and allowed the band to host the ''[[Once Upon a Tour]]'', concluded in Finland on October 21, 2005, when they played their last concert with Turunen on vocals and also when the ''[[End of an Era|End of an Era DVD]]'' was recorded. In May 2007, former [[Alyson Avenue]] frontwoman [[Anette Olzon]] was revealed as Turunen's replacement,<ref name="mape3">{{cite book|first1=Mape|last1= Ollila|first2= Olga|last2= Pohjola|title= Dark Passion Play|publisher= Ville Akseli Juurikkala|location= Torpinkylä |year=2008|isbn = 978-952-92434-1-9|page=5|language=[[Finnish language|Finnish]]}}</ref> and the album ''[[Dark Passion Play]]'' was released on September 26 after the singles "[[Eva (single)|Eva]]" in May and "[[Amaranth (song)|Amaranth]]" in August.<ref name="nw bio" /> 

The next Nightwish single, "[[Storytime (song)|Storytime]]", was released on November 9, 2011, and the seventh studio album, ''[[Imaginaerum]]'', will come out on December 2 alongside a [[Imaginaerum (film)|movie of the same name]], directed by Stobe Harju, who previously directed Nightwish's "The Islander" music video.<ref name="img">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nightwish.com/en/imaginaerumteaser|title=Imaginaerum|work=Nightwish.com|date=2011-09-09|accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref> The band is also scheduled to start the ''[[Imaginaerum World Tour]]'' in the [[USA]] city of [[Los Angeles]] on January 21, 2012, at the [[Gibson Amphitheatre]].<ref name="imgtour">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nightwish.com/en/news/?page=3|title=Nightwish kick off the Imaginarium World Tour in Los Angeles|work=Nightwish.com|date=2011-03-14|accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref>

